{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5cd146d0-7b87-4c82-94aa-5902a92ab63a","content":"For a .NET Web API, use the `dotnet new webapi` template. Authentication options you can pass via `--auth`:\n\n| Option | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `None` | No authentication (default) |\n| `IndividualB2C` | Azure AD B2C individual accounts |\n| `SingleOrg` | Single-tenant Azure AD |\n| `MultiOrg` | Multi-tenant Azure AD |\n| `Windows` | Windows authentication |\n\n**Examples:**\n\n```bash\n# Basic API with no auth\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi\n\n# With Azure AD single-org auth\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi --auth SingleOrg --domain yourdomain.onmicrosoft.com --tenant-id <id> --client-id <id>\n\n# With Azure AD B2C\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi --auth IndividualB2C\n```\n\nRun `dotnet new webapi --help` for the full list of options. For JWT bearer or custom auth, start with `None` and add `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer` via NuGet.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"20910078-3852-44b2-8f91-1991c5e58061","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":345,"requestId":"2814:3A3A20:11DC54:17682A:69FFD732"},"id":"0c9cdaf5-e1b3-4dc9-91b8-fb8e90c67a4c","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:54:17.890Z","parentId":"06d4ff65-719d-474c-9853-0f8a09066594"}
